To ensure proper synchronization of the serial input shift registers and the sum calculation process with the clock, you can make the following adjustments:

  1. Serial Input Shift Registers:

    • Use a clocked process to shift in the serial input values. This ensures that the input values change only at the rising edge of the clock, making the input stable for the duration of a clock cycle.
    • Modify the testbench stimulus process to change the input values (A_Serial and B_Serial) only at the rising edge of the clock.

  2. Sum Calculation:

    • Trigger the sum calculation process on the rising edge of the clock, ensuring that it is synchronized with the clock.
    • Instead of relying on flags (msb_loaded_A and msb_loaded_B) to determine when to perform the addition, you can directly trigger the addition process when both inputs are stable (after shifting in all bits).

Here's how you can adjust the code:

vhdl
-- Shift register process for input A
process (Clock_Main)
begin
    if rising_edge(Clock_Main) then
        A_reg <= A_reg(2 downto 0) & A_Serial; -- Shift left and insert serial data
        -- Optionally, you can reset msb_loaded_A here if needed
    end if;
end process;

-- Shift register process for input B
process (Clock_Main)
begin
    if rising_edge(Clock_Main) then
        B_reg <= B_reg(2 downto 0) & B_Serial; -- Shift left and insert serial data
        -- Optionally, you can reset msb_loaded_B here if needed
    end if;
end process;

-- Adder logic
process (Clock_Main)
begin
    if rising_edge(Clock_Main) then
        -- Perform addition when both inputs are stable
        internal_sum <= std_logic_vector(unsigned(A_reg) + unsigned(B_reg));
        Cout <= internal_sum(3);
        Sum <= internal_sum;
    end if;
end process;

And for the testbench:

vhdl
-- Stimulus process
stimulus: process
begin
    -- Initialize inputs
    A_Serial <= '0'; 
    B_Serial <= '0'; 
    Scan_Enable <= '0';
    wait for 10ns;

    -- Change input values at rising edge of Clock_Main
    wait until rising_edge(Clock_Main);
    A_Serial <= '1'; -- First bit of A
    B_Serial <= '1'; -- First bit of B
    wait for 10 ns;
    A_Serial <= '1'; -- Second bit of A
    B_Serial <= '0'; -- Second bit of B
    wait for 10 ns;
    A_Serial <= '0'; -- Third bit of A
    B_Serial <= '1'; -- Third bit of B
    wait for 10 ns;
    A_Serial <= '1'; -- Fourth bit of A
    B_Serial <= '0'; -- Fourth bit of B
    wait for 10 ns;

    -- Enable scan chain
    wait until rising_edge(Clock_Main);
    Scan_Enable <= '1';

    -- Allow time for scan chain to load
    wait for 10 ns;

    -- Disable scan chain to output values
    Scan_Enable <= '0';

    -- Stop simulation
    stop_the_clock <= true;
    wait;
end process;

These adjustments ensure that the serial input shift registers and the sum calculation process are synchronized properly with the clock, thereby addressing the first two points.

Flags can introduce additional complexity and potential synchronization challenges if not managed properly. Here's how you can ensure that using flags for controlling the addition process doesn't lead to issues:

  1. Synchronization: Make sure that the flags are updated synchronously with the clock. This means that the conditions under which the flags are set or reset should be triggered by rising edges of the clock signals. In your original code, you're using clocked processes to update the flags, which is a good approach.

  2. Resetting Flags: If you choose to reset the flags after the addition operation, ensure that the reset operation is synchronized with the clock and occurs at the appropriate time. Resetting the flags too early or too late could lead to incorrect behavior.

  3. Flag Dependency: Ensure that the addition process depends only on the flags and not on any other asynchronous signals. If there are other signals that affect the addition process, make sure they are properly synchronized with the clock to avoid timing issues.

By carefully managing the synchronization of flags with the clock and ensuring that the addition process is correctly dependent on these flags, you can minimize the risk of issues arising from their use. If you want to deserialize the input (convert serial input to parallel) before performing the sum, you can modify the code to shift in the serial input into shift registers and then deserialize it to obtain parallel inputs for addition. Here's how you can do it:

vhdl
-- Deserialize inputs
process (Clock_Main)
begin
    if rising_edge(Clock_Main) then
        -- Shift in serial input A
        A_reg <= A_reg(2 downto 0) & A_Serial;
        
        -- Shift in serial input B
        B_reg <= B_reg(2 downto 0) & B_Serial;
        
        -- Perform deserialization when all bits are shifted in
        if A_reg(3) = '1' and B_reg(3) = '1' then
            A_deserialized <= A_reg;
            B_deserialized <= B_reg;
        end if;
    end if;
end process;

-- Adder logic
process (Clock_Main)
begin
    if rising_edge(Clock_Main) then
        -- Perform addition when both inputs are deserialized
        if A_reg(3) = '1' and B_reg(3) = '1' then
            internal_sum <= std_logic_vector(unsigned(A_deserialized) + unsigned(B_deserialized));
            Cout <= internal_sum(3);
            Sum <= internal_sum;
        end if;
    end if;
end process;

In this modified code:

  1. The serial input (A_Serial and B_Serial) is shifted into shift registers (A_reg and B_reg) on every rising edge of Clock_Main.
  2. Once all bits are shifted in (when the MSBs of A_reg and B_reg are both '1'), the inputs are deserialized (copied to A_deserialized and B_deserialized).
  3. The addition process checks if both inputs are deserialized, and if so, performs the addition using the deserialized inputs.

This approach ensures that the addition is performed only when all bits of both inputs have been shifted in and deserialized. It separates the serialization/deserialization process from the addition process, allowing for better control and synchronization.
